## 🎯 Purpose

This document outlines the step-by-step process for identifying, containing, eradicating, and recovering from a security incident.

-----

## 📊 Incident Severity Levels

|Level|Name    |Description                                 |Response Time  |
|-----|--------|--------------------------------------------|---------------|
|1    |Critical|Active breach, data exfiltration, ransomware|Immediate      |
|2    |High    |Suspected compromise, malware detected      |Within 1 hour  |
|3    |Medium  |Policy violation, suspicious activity       |Within 4 hours |
|4    |Low     |Minor anomaly, false positive investigation |Within 24 hours|

-----

## 🔄 Response Phases

### Phase 1 — Preparation

- [ ] Incident response team identified and trained
- [ ] Communication channels established
- [ ] Tools and access confirmed
- [ ] Playbooks documented

### Phase 2 — Identification

- [ ] Alert or report received
- [ ] Initial triage performed
- [ ] Severity level assigned
- [ ] Incident ticket created
- [ ] Stakeholders notified

**Key Questions:**

- What systems are affected?
- When was it first detected?
- How was it detected?
- Is it still ongoing?

### Phase 3 — Containment

- [ ] Short-term containment applied (isolate affected systems)
- [ ] Evidence preserved (logs, snapshots)
- [ ] Long-term containment strategy defined
- [ ] Business impact assessed

### Phase 4 — Eradication

- [ ] Root cause identified
- [ ] Malware/threat removed
- [ ] Vulnerabilities patched
- [ ] Systems hardened

### Phase 5 — Recovery

- [ ] Systems restored from clean backups
- [ ] Functionality verified
- [ ] Monitoring increased
- [ ] Stakeholders updated

### Phase 6 — Lessons Learned

- [ ] Post-incident review scheduled (within 2 weeks)
- [ ] Timeline documented
- [ ] What went well?
- [ ] What needs improvement?
- [ ] Process updates made

